<subSubSection id="15DE5FE0FF9EEF5DFF42FEFFFE30FD3C" pageId="54" pageNumber="55" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="5D7B0C6BFF9EEF5DFF42FEFFFDD8FE4C" blockId="54.[151,1437,257,537]" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">
<emphasis id="6FB0D079FF9EEF5DFF42FEFFFEE7FEDC" bold="true" box="[199,338,330,356]" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">Comments:</emphasis>
This species seems also to be more restricted to southern South America, just like 
<taxonomicName id="9AC477E8FF9EEF5DFB6BFEFEFA20FEDC" authorityName="Emsley" authorityYear="1970" box="[1262,1429,330,357]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Stilpnochlora" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="54" pageNumber="55" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="marginoides">
<emphasis id="6FB0D079FF9EEF5DFB6BFEFEFA20FEDC" box="[1262,1429,330,357]" italics="true" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">S. marginoides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. At first, we could interpret that this is the first record of the species for a forested area. However, we cannot dismiss the possibility that the records for 
<collectingRegion id="9F00C289FF9EEF5DFD9AFE27FD3EFE14" box="[543,651,402,428]" country="Argentina" name="Tucuman" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">Tucumán</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingCountry id="25D34CFBFF9EEF5DFD13FE27FCBDFE14" box="[662,776,402,428]" name="Argentina" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">Argentina</collectingCountry>
, and Santo Domingo de 
<collectingRegion id="9F00C289FF9EEF5DFBA6FE27FBCFFE14" box="[1059,1146,402,428]" country="Uruguay" name="Soriano" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">Soriano</collectingRegion>
(Villa 
<collectingRegion id="9F00C289FF9EEF5DFB4FFE27FA90FE15" box="[1226,1317,402,429]" country="Uruguay" name="Soriano" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">Soriano</collectingRegion>
), 
<collectingCountry id="25D34CFBFF9EEF5DFABFFE26FA29FE15" box="[1338,1436,403,429]" name="Uruguay" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">Uruguay</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation id="3955719AFF9EEF5DFF1AFE03FE83FE68" author="Emsley, M." box="[159,310,438,464]" pageId="54" pageNumber="55" pagination="125 - 248" refId="ref31846" refString="Emsley, M. (1970) A revision of the Steirodontine katydids (Orthoptera: Tettigoniidae: Phaneropterinae: Steirodontini). Academy of Natural Sciences, 122, 125 - 248." type="journal article" year="1970">Emsley 1970</bibRefCitation>
) corresponds to specimens collected in forested areas, respectively in the Yungas and in forests associated to the Negro and 
<collectingCountry id="25D34CFBFF9EEF5DFE39FE6EFDABFE4D" box="[444,542,475,501]" name="Uruguay" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">Uruguay</collectingCountry>
rivers.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5D7B0C6BFF9EEF5DFF42FE4BFDFBFDA0" blockId="54.[151,1437,257,537]" box="[199,590,510,537]" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">
<emphasis id="6FB0D079FF9EEF5DFF42FE4BFED1FDA0" bold="true" box="[199,356,510,536]" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">Bioacoustics:</emphasis>
Sound not recorded.
</paragraph>
